Syria 'clear' to return refugees, according to Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria says to be ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country that has been destroyed by a war of more than seven years.
During his speech to the UN General Assembly, Minister for Foreign Affairs, Walid al-Moualem, declared that the circumstances in his country improve.
"Today, the situation on the spot is more stable and safe, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he says.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas that have been destroyed by terrorists and to normalize the situation on the spot.
All the circumstances now exist for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that threatened their daily lives and existence.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have escaped their country since the war began in 2011.
It is estimated that there are still some six million people living in the country who need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would welcome help in restoring the destroyed country.
However, he stressed that Syria would not accept conditional assistance or assistance from countries that had subsidized the rebellion.
