Red gloed update: Concentrations are taking place in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The most recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (Florida Commission for the Conservation of Fish and Fauna) shows a general decline in Rode Gloed concentrations in parts of Tampa Bay Area (city on the western coast of Florida in the USA).
According to the committee, a fragmentary increase in the Red Gloed in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier could indicate a fall in concentrations.
The Red Glow extends over an average of 200 km coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern Lee counties.
There are approximately 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County spots, but in less places than last week.
Rode has also been seen in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported for the coast of Pinellas County last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
It is permanently reported on irritation of airways in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no mention was made of irritation of airways during the last week.
